    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In Java 8:</p>\n\n<pre><code>String[] strings = list.parallelStream().toArray(String[]::new);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6411785,
      "reputation" : 1903,
      "user_id" : 4971315,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 45,
      "profile_image" : "https://graph.facebook.com/10206972837629356/picture?type=large",
      "display_name" : "Roberto Attias",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4971315/roberto-attias"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1696469603,
    "last_edit_date" : 1696469603,
    "creation_date" : 1483569420,
    "answer_id" : 41474402,
    "question_id" : 4042434,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In case some extra manipulation of the data is desired, for which the user wants a function, this approach is not perfect (as it requires passing the class of the element as second parameter), but works:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>import java.util.ArrayList;\nimport java.lang.reflect.Array;\n\npublic class Test {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; al = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\n    al.add(1);\n    al.add(2);\n    Integer[] arr = convert(al, Integer.class);\n    for (int i=0; i&lt;arr.length; i++)\n      System.out.println(arr[i]);\n  }\n\n  public static &lt;T&gt; T[] convert(ArrayList&lt;T&gt; al, Class clazz) {\n    return (T[]) al.toArray((T[])Array.newInstance(clazz, al.size()));\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 128453,
        "reputation" : 798,
        "user_id" : 326294,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c4e920539a371eb9decd0c81290ca28c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Alain BECKER",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/326294/alain-becker"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1622973706,
      "post_id" : 44049143,
      "comment_id" : 119940382,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "If <i>generics</i> has a meaning, wouldn&#39;t it rather be &quot;convert any List&lt;Type&gt; to Type[]&quot;?"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1342249,
      "reputation" : 8179,
      "user_id" : 1283715,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 74,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/n0LVK.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Khaled Lela",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1283715/khaled-lela"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1522848232,
    "last_edit_date" : 1522848232,
    "creation_date" : 1495114146,
    "answer_id" : 44049143,
    "question_id" : 4042434,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><strong>Generics</strong> solution to covert any <code>List&lt;Type&gt;</code> to <code>String []</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public static  &lt;T&gt; String[] listToArray(List&lt;T&gt; list) {\n    String [] array = new String[list.size()];\n    for (int i = 0; i &lt; array.length; i++)\n        array[i] = list.get(i).toString();\n    return array;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Note</strong> You must <code>override toString()</code> method.</p>\n\n<pre><code>class Car {\n  private String name;\n  public Car(String name) {\n    this.name = name;\n  }\n  public String toString() {\n    return name;\n  }\n}\nfinal List&lt;Car&gt; carList = new ArrayList&lt;Car&gt;();\ncarList.add(new Car(\"BMW\"))\ncarList.add(new Car(\"Mercedes\"))\ncarList.add(new Car(\"Skoda\"))\nfinal String[] carArray = listToArray(carList);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 60521,
        "reputation" : 35765,
        "user_id" : 180719,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 88,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/AWsdT.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Olivier Gr&#233;goire",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/180719/olivier-gr%c3%a9goire"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1503911103,
      "post_id" : 45915002,
      "comment_id" : 78789111,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "I downvoted because: 1. no use of generics which force you into 2. using <code>.toString()</code> where no explicit cast would be needed, 3. you don&#39;t even increment <code>i</code>, and 4. the <code>while</code> would be better off replaced by a <code>for</code>. Suggested code: <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt; stringList = ... ; String[] stringArray = new String[stringList.size()]; int i = 0; for(Iterator&lt;String&gt; it = stringList.iterator(); it.hasNext(); i++) { stringArray[i] = it.next(); }</code>"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 11237496,
      "reputation" : 129,
      "user_id" : 8243078,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-03XFjRcipcA/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAfY/re2M0rHfigo/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
      "display_name" : "Vatsal Chavda",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8243078/vatsal-chavda"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1522848172,
    "last_edit_date" : 1522848172,
    "creation_date" : 1503909796,
    "answer_id" : 45915002,
    "question_id" : 4042434,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can use <strong><code>Iterator&lt;String&gt;</code></strong> to iterate the elements of the <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\nString[] array = new String[list.size()];\nint i = 0;\nfor (Iterator&lt;String&gt; iterator = list.iterator(); iterator.hasNext(); i++) {\n    array[i] = iterator.next();\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Now you can retrive elements from <code>String[]</code> using any Loop.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6301592,
      "reputation" : 436,
      "user_id" : 5303000,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-ltyK2dOmsoo/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAABE/WJpLbp6gt38/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
      "display_name" : "Denis Fedak",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5303000/denis-fedak"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1514366881,
    "creation_date" : 1514366881,
    "answer_id" : 47989547,
    "question_id" : 4042434,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<pre><code>private String[] prepareDeliveryArray(List&lt;DeliveryServiceModel&gt; deliveryServices) {\n    String[] delivery = new String[deliveryServices.size()];\n    for (int i = 0; i &lt; deliveryServices.size(); i++) {\n        delivery[i] = deliveryServices.get(i).getName();\n    }\n    return delivery;\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 12145950,
      "reputation" : 5524,
      "user_id" : 8868289,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/984bb123a4de58126dc1166e43927c5a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Yoory N.",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8868289/yoory-n"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1518614207,
    "creation_date" : 1518614207,
    "answer_id" : 48788179,
    "question_id" : 4042434,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If your application is already using Apache Commons lib, you can slightly modify the accepted answer to not create a new empty array each time:</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; list = ..;\nString[] array = list.toArray(ArrayUtils.EMPTY_STRING_ARRAY);\n\n// or if using static import\nString[] array = list.toArray(EMPTY_STRING_ARRAY);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>There are a few more preallocated empty arrays of different types in <code>ArrayUtils</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Also we can trick JVM to create en empty array for us this way:</p>\n\n<pre><code>String[] array = list.toArray(ArrayUtils.toArray());\n\n// or if using static import\nString[] array = list.toArray(toArray());\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>But there's really no advantage this way, just a matter of taste, IMO.</p>\n"
  }, {
