    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6800611,
      "reputation" : 159,
      "user_id" : 5234024,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a96a9fd97e5905db5c4333564ccc003e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "nick w.",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5234024/nick-w"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1574710095,
    "last_edit_date" : 1574710095,
    "creation_date" : 1550732139,
    "answer_id" : 54800959,
    "question_id" : 4042434,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<pre><code>    List&lt;String&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\n    list.add(\"a\");\n    list.add(\"b\");\n    list.add(\"c\");\n    String [] strArry= list.stream().toArray(size -&gt; new String[size]);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Per comments, I have added a paragraph to explain how the conversion works. \nFirst, List is converted to a String stream. Then it uses Stream.toArray to convert the elements in the stream to an Array. In the last statement above \"size -> new String[size]\" is actually an IntFunction function that allocates a String array with the size of the String stream. The statement is identical to</p>\n\n<pre><code>IntFunction&lt;String []&gt; allocateFunc = size -&gt; { \nreturn new String[size];\n};   \nString [] strArry= list.stream().toArray(allocateFunc);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
